# FinTrack ‚Äî Project-Wide Code Quality Rules

## Project Context
- **App name:** FinTrack ‚Äî personal finance management SPA
- **Frontend:** Angular 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS v4, RxJS, Chart.js
- **Backend:** Spring Boot 3.3, Java 21, MySQL 8, AWS Elastic Beanstalk
- **Lambdas:** PDF generator, budget alert scheduler
- **Repo:** `fintrack-fullstack` monorepo
- **Frontend root:** `fintrack-ui/`
- **Backend root:** `fintrack-api/`

## Code Quality ‚Äî Universal
- Write correct, bug-free, fully working code ‚Äî never output placeholder logic like `// TODO: implement`
- Every function must do one thing ‚Äî if you can describe it with "and", split it
- Fail fast: validate inputs at the top of functions, return early on invalid state
- Happy path last: handle errors and edge cases before the success path
- No magic numbers or magic strings ‚Äî extract to named constants
- No commented-out code ‚Äî delete it, that is what git history is for
- No `console.log` left in committed code ‚Äî use the logger service

## Naming Conventions

### Angular (TypeScript)
- Components: `PascalCase` ‚Äî `TransactionListComponent`
- Services: `PascalCase` + `Service` suffix ‚Äî `TransactionService`
- Pipes: `PascalCase` + `Pipe` suffix ‚Äî `CurrencyZarPipe`
- Guards: `camelCase` + `Guard` suffix ‚Äî `authGuard`
- Signals: `camelCase` ‚Äî `currentUser`, `isLoading`
- Observables: `camelCase$` suffix ‚Äî `transactions$`
- Interfaces/Types: `PascalCase`, no `I` prefix ‚Äî `Transaction`, not `ITransaction`
- Enums: `PascalCase` with `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` values ‚Äî `BudgetStatus.ON_TRACK`
- Files: `kebab-case` ‚Äî `transaction-list.component.ts`

### Java/Spring Boot
- Classes: `PascalCase` ‚Äî `TransactionService`
- Methods: `camelCase` ‚Äî `findByUserAndDateRange()`
- Constants: `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`
- Packages: `lowercase` ‚Äî `com.fintrack.transaction`
- REST endpoints: `kebab-case` plural nouns ‚Äî `/api/v1/transactions`
- DTOs: suffix with `Request` or `Response` ‚Äî `CreateTransactionRequest`, `TransactionResponse`

## API Contract Rules (Frontend)
- All API calls go through the service layer ‚Äî components never call `HttpClient` directly
- All responses unwrap the `ApiResponse<T>` wrapper using `.pipe(map(res => res.data))`
- All paginated responses use `PagedResponse<T>` ‚Äî never assume a flat array from list endpoints
- Error handling: 404 and 422 are handled at the component level; 0, 403, 500 are handled by the interceptor
- Never hardcode API URLs in components ‚Äî always use `environment.apiBaseUrl`

## API Contract Rules (Backend)
- All responses wrapped in `ApiResponse<T>` ‚Äî never return a raw object from a controller
- All list endpoints are paginated ‚Äî no endpoint returns an unbounded list
- All endpoints validate input with Bean Validation ‚Äî `@Valid` on every `@RequestBody`
- All user-specific queries include `WHERE user_id = :currentUserId` ‚Äî never trust a client-supplied userId
- Soft deletes only: set `deleted_at = NOW()` ‚Äî never `DELETE FROM` in application code

## State Management Rules (Frontend)
- Use Angular Signals for all UI state and shared service state
- `signal()` for mutable state, `computed()` for derived values, `effect()` for side effects only
- Loading state: every service that makes HTTP calls must expose a `loading` signal
- Error state: errors are shown via `ToastService`, not stored in component state
- No component stores data it doesn't own ‚Äî always read from the service's signal

## Git & Commit Rules
- Use Conventional Commits: `feat:`, `fix:`, `docs:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `test:`, `style:`
- Subject line max 72 characters, imperative mood: "Add auth interceptor" not "Added auth interceptor"
- One logical change per commit ‚Äî don't bundle unrelated changes
- Never commit: `.env` files, `node_modules/`, compiled output, IDE config files (`.idea/`, `.vscode/`)
- Branch naming: `feature/transaction-filters`, `fix/budget-calculation`, `chore/update-deps`

## Security Rules
- Never log passwords, tokens, or PII ‚Äî scrub sensitive fields before logging
- Never store the JWT secret or DB password in code ‚Äî always read from environment variables
- Never disable CORS broadly with `*` in production ‚Äî use the `ALLOWED_ORIGINS` env var
- All user inputs are validated server-side regardless of client-side validation
- Pre-signed S3 URLs expire in 5 minutes ‚Äî never extend this TTL

## Performance Rules (Frontend)
- Use `OnPush` on every component ‚Äî this is mandatory, not optional
- Lazy-load all feature routes ‚Äî never import a feature component at the app level
- Use `trackBy: item.id` on every `@for` loop rendering a list from the API
- Debounce all search/filter inputs by 300ms before triggering an API call
- Avoid subscribing to the same observable twice ‚Äî use `shareReplay(1)` or a signal

## Performance Rules (Backend)
- Never use `SELECT *` ‚Äî always name required columns in JPQL/SQL
- All list queries must be paginated with `Pageable` ‚Äî no `findAll()` without pagination
- Add `@Index` on all foreign key columns and frequently filtered columns
- Avoid N+1 queries ‚Äî use `JOIN FETCH` or `@EntityGraph` where associations are needed
- Log a `WARN` for any request that takes longer than 500ms (handled by `RequestLoggingAspect`)

## Documentation Rules
- Every public service method must have a JSDoc/Javadoc comment explaining what it does
- Every REST endpoint must have a `@Operation` (SpringDoc) annotation with a summary
- Every Angular `@Input` signal must have a JSDoc comment if its purpose isn't obvious from the name
- The `README.md` at the repo root must always be up to date with setup instructions
